04535nmm a2200685Ia 9781501706028DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)964529094  a(OCoLC)979581599  a97815017060287 a10.7591/97815017060282doi  a(DE-B1597)478712  a(OCoLC)957590819  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aRA395.A3bG527 201704a362.104252231 aGivan, Rebecca Kolins, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Challenge to Change :bReforming Health Care on the Front Line in the United States and the United Kingdom /cRebecca Kolins Givan. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Culture and Politics of Health Care Work0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is constant pressure on hospitals to improve health care delivery and increase cost effectiveness. New initiatives are the order of the day in the dramatically different health care systems of the United States and Great Britain. Often, as we know all too well, these efforts are not successful. In The Challenge to Change, Rebecca Kolins Givan analyzes the successes and failures of efforts to improve hospitals and explains what factors make it likely that the implementation of reforms will rewarded by positive transformation in a particular institution’s day-to-day operation. Givan’s in-depth qualitative case studies of both top-down initiatives and changes first suggested by staff on the front lines of care point clearly to the importance of all hospital workers in effecting change and even influencing national policy.Givan illuminates the critical role of workers, managers, and unions in enabling or constraining changes in policies and procedures and ensuring their implementation. Givan spotlights an Anglo-American model of hospital care and work organization, even while these countries retain their differences in access and payment. Entrenched professional roles, hierarchical workplace organization, and the sometimes-detached view of policymakers all shape the prospects for change in hospitals. Givan provides important examples of how the dedication and imagination of the people who work in hospitals can make all the difference when it comes to providing quality health care even in a challenging economic environment.  afunded by NEH CARES grant  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aHealth care reformzGreat Britain. 0aHealth care reformzUnited States. 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aMedicine & Medical Issues.2 aNEH CARES grantefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics 2016z9783110485158oZDB-23-DBV40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170602840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501706028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501706028/original  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DBVb2016  aZDB-23-DGGb2016